Title: Which (Rhyming) Poem is Better?
Description: Read two poems and rate them
Input.Title: COLORS (Where the Sidewalk Ends)
Input.Poem:
My skin is kind of sort of brownish

Pinkish yellowish white.

My eyes are grayish blueish green,

But I’m told they look orange in the night.

My hair is reddish blondish brown,

But it’s silver when it’s wet.

And all the colors I am inside

Have not been invented yet.
Input.first_line: My skin is kind of sort of brownish
Input.line1: my skin is too
Input.line2: the colour of my hair is clownish
Input.line3: even my friends call me winnie the pooh
Input.line4: The ground it calls me kin sometimes
Input.line5: brown birds croon at my hair
Input.line6: But here's my little secret friends
Input.line7: I dream of being fair
Answer.reason: Both poems are doggerel, but Poem 1 slightly better than Poem 2. The voice in Poem 1 belongs to a more expansive personality who sees no inherent limits for themselves ("All the colors I am inside have not been invented yet.")   Poem 2 has an unsatisfying meter. Although the images are unusual, the very last line ("I dream of being fair") is a little sad.  It's a turn-off.

I came to the spot that said, “Dig right here.”

And four feet down my spade struck wood

Just where the map said a chest would appear.

Title: Which (Rhyming) Poem is Better?
Description: Read two poems and rate them
Input.Title: COMPLAININ‚Äô JACK (Falling Up)
Input.Poem:
This morning my old jack-in-the-box

Popped out—and wouldn’t get back-in-the-box.

He cried, “Hey, there’s a tack-in-the-box,

And it’s cutting me through and through.”

“There also is a crack-in-the-box,

And I never find a smack-in-the-box,

And sometimes I hear a quack-in-the-box,

‘Cause a duck lives in here, too.”

Complain, complain is all he did—

I finally had to close the lid.
Input.first_line: This morning my old jack-in-the-box
Input.line1: Refused to open and close
Input.line2: The old lid stuck half way up
Input.line3: Barely missing his nose.
Input.line4: Jack tenderly felt his bright red nose
Input.line5: And said with a tear in his eye,
Input.line6: "Close the lid, you dunderhead,
Input.line7: Before you make me die!"
Answer.reason: I liked the imagery in poem one. It would be fun to read with a little kid.
